  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a serious criminal offense and is typically classified as a felony in most jurisdictions, including the United States. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally obtained money (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear legitimate by concealing its true origin. This can be done through various complex financial transactions and schemes.\n\nIn the United States, money laundering is prosecuted under federal law, primarily under the **Money Laundering Control Act (MLCA)** of 1986 (18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957). The penalties for money laundering can be severe and may include:\n\n- **Imprisonment**: Up to 20 years in federal prison for each count of money laundering.\n- **Fines**: Substantial fines, which can be up to $500,000 or twice the value of the laundered funds, whichever is greater.\n- **Asset Forfeiture**: The government can seize assets involved in or derived from money laundering activities.\n\nIndividual states also have their own laws against money laundering, and penalties can vary but are similarly severe.\n\nMoney laundering is a global issue, and many countries have stringent laws and international agreements, such as those by the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, to combat it. The consequences of a conviction can extend beyond legal penalties, including damage to one\u2019s reputation, loss of professional licenses, and restrictions on future financial activities.",
